    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" hidden-when-empty="true">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors />
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>29</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008N/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>008N</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/008N/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Counterexamples">Counterexamples</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>    Okay; those are our models.
    To get a logic from these, we need to do the usual model-theoretic thing.
    That is, we need to say which models are counterexamples to which arguments.
    As you might expect, this will make use of the values assigned by the models at various points.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    In fact, it's easiest to say what it takes for a <html:em>point</html:em> in a model to be a counterexample to an argument.
    A model then gets to be a counterexample to an argument by containing a point that's a counterexample to that argument.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008O/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008O</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008O/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuitionistic counterexample">Intuitionistic counterexample</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>    A point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in a model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is a <html:strong>counterexample</html:strong> to the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> when it meets two conditions:
<html:ul><html:li>for every sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(B, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>; and</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(A, x) = ?]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
    This is basically just a designated-value approach again, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> designated and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> undesignated, except that we need to remember that sentences need both a model and a point in that model to get any value at all.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    Before we see some examples, let me remind you: the logic this determines is exactly intuitionistic logic, the same logic determined by the proof system NJ.
    That is, if an argument has a proof in NJ, then no model provides a counterexample to it; and if an argument has no proof in NJ, then there is a model that provides a counterexample to it.
    So all the examples of counterexamples will be to arguments that have no proof in NJ, since those are the only arguments that have any counterexamples at all.</html:p>
            <html:p>Do note that, at least for now, you have to trust me on this: that these models determine the same logic as the proof system NJ.
That's certainly not obvious!
And we haven't looked at all at why it might be so.
But it is indeed so.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008P/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008P</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008P/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Examples of intuitionistic counterexamples">Examples of intuitionistic counterexamples</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008Q/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>008Q</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/008Q/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>        You might recall that in intuitionistic logic, the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> is not valid.
        So it must have a counterexample.
        Here is one:</html:p>
                    <html:p>
                      <fr:resource hash="f1a7d0a3f6c04d5be23e616b23fbb414">
                        <fr:resource-content>
                          <html:img src="/lectures/f1a7d0a3f6c04d5be23e616b23fbb414.svg" />
                        </fr:resource-content>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
         1: \{\} \arrow [r] & 2: \{p\}
        \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                      </fr:resource>
                    </html:p>
                    <html:p>In this model, both points assign <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>; this is because each of them can reach some point that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
        (For both points, this reachable place is 2.)
</html:p>
                    <html:p>        Because of this, in turn, both points assign <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p]]></fr:tex>; neither of them can reach anywhere in the model that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        So 1 assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  \neg  p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>; it is our counterexample, as it occurs in this model.
</html:p>
                    <html:p>        Here's how you might interpret this: in intuitionistic logic, we might see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> as saying something like "I know something that rules out my ever coming to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>".
        And we might know something that rules out our ever coming to know something that rules out our ever coming to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, without yet actually knowing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
                    <html:p>        Looking at this model, we've got a situation at the point 1 where we don't yet know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, but there's no way in the model to ever come to know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        So we <html:em>do</html:em> know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg  p]]></fr:tex>.
        That means that the argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg \neg  p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> can have a known premise and an unknown conclusion, so intuitionistic logic judges it invalid.
</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>29</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008R/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>008R</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/008R/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>        Here's another example: in intuitionistic logic, the argument from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \land  q) \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  r) \lor  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> fails.
        So it must have a counterexample.
        Here is one: let the model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> be:
</html:p>
                    <html:p>
                      <fr:resource hash="ffd46402b0f460c1308e31e9fd96ff36">
                        <fr:resource-content>
                          <html:img src="/lectures/ffd46402b0f460c1308e31e9fd96ff36.svg" />
                        </fr:resource-content>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[        \begin {tikzcd}
         & 4 : \{p, q, r\}\\
        2: \{p\} \arrow [ur] & & 3: \{q\} \arrow [ul]\\
        & 1: \{\} \arrow [ur] \arrow [ul] &\\
        \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source>
                      </fr:resource>
                    </html:p>
                    <html:p>        Now, think about the values of the sentences in the argument at the point 1 in this model.
        We have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M((p \land  q) \rightarrow  r, 1) = Y]]></fr:tex>, since the only point reachable from 1 that assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex> in this model is 4, and 4 also assigns <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.
        But both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> get value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at 1, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> because of the presence of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[2]]></fr:tex> in the model and for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  r]]></fr:tex> because of the presence of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[3]]></fr:tex> in the model.
        So their disjunction also gets a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>.
        This gives the premise of this argument getting a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> in this model, and the conclusion getting a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[?]]></fr:tex> there.
        So we have our counterexample.
</html:p>
                    <html:p>        This model pictures a certain kind of dependency: if we have both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, then we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> as well, but neither <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> nor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> on its own is enough for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.
        This is a common kind of dependency: everything from light switches to the law includes situations where two things need to come together to suffice for something else, where neither one would suffice on its own.
        Our intuitionistic models can picture this very straightforwardly, as this example shows.
</html:p>
                    <html:p>        However, <html:em>all</html:em> of the logics K3, LP, FDE, and classical logic validate this argument.
        So this seems to be one way in which intuitionistic implication is more flexible than the implications of all those logics.
</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
